##Ask Cao Bin: How's the ridgway trial going?

Micro Signal deeptechchina

Function description DeepTech is a full-chain content, service, data and investment and financing platform focusing on the emerging technology industrialization, and is committed to building a global network of scientific and technological innovation cooperation.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
What about the Ridgeway test? Cao Bin, deputy director of the China Japan Friendship Hospital and the host of the project, gave an update on the progress of the remarkable trial in an online broadcast on March 1.

Cao Bin was one of the first members of the national panel. He arrived in Wuhan on the afternoon of December 31,2019, and the live broadcast on March 1 was also held at Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital. As early as New Year's Day this year, he co-authored the Wuhan viral pneumonia of unknown causes (pilot edition) , which is also the basis of the first edition of the COVID-19.

For more than a decade, Cao Bin has been studying community acquired pneumonia. In 2019, they published a number of studies, one of which was to examine the viral profiles of adult community acquired pneumonia, especially viral pneumonia, in 13 provinces of China, the incidence, severity and prognosis of influenza virus pneumonia and non-influenza virus pneumonia were analyzed.

During the new crown disease, the Cao Bin Group led three clinical studies, including the Klebsiella (Lopelavir / Ritonavir) and two studies of Radzivir (Radzivir mild or moderate disease study, Radzivir intensive study) .

There are now more than 230 studies in the Radzivir Intensive Care Group, Cao Bin said, and they have reached the sample size required for mid term analysis. Another study, the Kritzy clinical trial, was formally completed with 199 prospective, randomized, controlled clinical trials.

Image | Cao Bin on air source: screenshot

The article is based on the live broadcast text of the public number "aspiration" on Wechat, which is co-sponsored by the Chinese Medical Association and the Chinese Medical Association. DEEPTECH did a recap. The answers below are from Cao Bin.

Question 1: Why is Ridgway chosen as the study target?

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
For an infectious disease, oxygen therapy, breathing machines, nutritional support therapy, balance of water and electrolytes, prophylactic antibiotics, and hormones recommended by some doctors are all complementary. The most fundamental is the treatment of cause.

Cao Bin said the drug came into his field of vision after Kreutzer, in early January 2020. "before I left Wuhan on January 9, I had our second target in Reutseville, " he said.

Coincidentally, an article had just been published online in the journal Nature Communications, it was an animal study by a team of doctors at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, who infected mice with MERS coronavirus, or Mers, and looked at two drugs, one is Klebsiella plus Interferon, the same treatment regimen used for SARS and Mers, and the other is Redoxivir.

Ridgeville protected mice from lung damage as well as mortality, and its ability to reduce viral titers was remarkable. It was a big shock to them, Cao Bin says. That said, whether it was SARS or Mers, at least in animal models, the Klebsiella plus interferon regimen they used was not nearly as effective as Radzivir.

In November 2019, the Journal The New England Journal of Medicine published a study of Redesivir in humans. The human study was conducted on the Zaire Ebolavirus, but it gave Cao Bin confidence that at least one human trial of Radzivir had been conducted on humans and that he could see the safety data.

Question 2: What are the characteristics of the REDESIVIR intensive care trial compared to the KLIEG study?

The two groups were both patients with severe and critically ill pneumonia, but there was one difference. The KRIEGE study did not limit the time from onset of illness to entry into the group. The study design for the Radzivir group was more rigorous because antiviral treatment should be given as early as possible, so we stuck the antiviral time at 12 days, which is less than 12 days from the onset of the disease.

That's what Cao Bin's team learned from studying the flu virus. If patients who had been in the hospital for more than 20 days were readmitted to the group, even if they were eventually cured, it would be impossible to know for sure whether antiviral drug worked.

Cao Bin said, "We were stuck on 12 days when we did the design for the Radziev Intensive Care Unit, and we were struggling with whether it was better to be stuck on 10 days, 12 days or 14 days. It was a difficult decision. "

Question 3: How to choose the outcome indicator of the study?

The mild-to-moderate design is completely different from the severe design, and in fact these are two completely different clinical studies.

For severe new coronary pneumonia, researchers are concerned about the "hard end" , that is, the outcome of death and disability. The 28-day case-fatality rate was included in the composite end-point index in the severe redesivir study, but when the 28-day case-fatality rate was used, the sample size requirement was very high. So ridgway was designed to have 453 people in intensive care.

For patients with mild illness, although it is not ruled out that a very small number of patients with mild illness will become seriously ill, researchers need to first understand which patients can become seriously ill and identify patients with severe risk factors, and then we're going to use this population as a subject. The criteria for admission must meet two criteria, one is mild pneumonia, the other is a risk factor for severe illness.

Question 4: How is the mid-term analysis in the Ridgway experiment designed?

Similar to the U. S. protocol, there was in fact a design for a mid-term analysis in the Chinese RADZIVIR ICU study. The mid term analysis was not conducted by researchers, it was conducted by an independent security committee or data management committee, and the China Program's Independent Committee consisted of five people, two of whom were domestic experts, three were foreign experts, including one from the United States, one from Canada and one from the United Kingdom. Three of the five were statistical and the other two were clinical experts who could see the data in the background and judge it.

Independent Committee members were also given the opportunity to systematically review the progress of the project and to observe differences in treatment outcomes between the two groups in real time. The effect is likely to be increasingly discrete, Cao Bin says, although it is in fact double blind, randomized placebo controlled trials. "If ridgway is effective, then the dispersion will become more and more apparent. "

There are three possibilities for this study. One is that the adverse effects of Radzivir have resulted in unexpected deaths and therefore increased mortality. The other is that Radzivir is effective and the case fatality rate has decreased. But the difference would have to be seen in the background by the Independent Commission when a certain number of selected cases accumulated. The third possibility is that Ridgeville is ineffective and harmless.

If it proves effective, the trial will be discontinued and all patients will be advised to use it. If the other case, the side effects are particularly large, but also must stop the experiment, the drug was "shot" off, and will never be allowed to carry out clinical research in humans.

Question 5: What are the latest results from the ridgway trial?

There are now more than 230 patients in the Radzivir Intensive Care Group, which has reached the sample size required for mid-term analysis. But just because you're in the group doesn't mean you can be evaluated, and you need 28 days of follow-up. This is not to say that it is necessarily 28 days, as long as the clinical outcome is achieved can be evaluated.

"As researchers, we're also looking forward to the possibility that a node could emerge when more than 230 patients reach clinical outcomes? This node would allow the Independent Safety Board to make an objective, scientific assessment, and if that were to happen, we wouldn't need to enroll 453 patients, we could enroll 400 or 300 patients."

Question 6: What is the relationship between evidence-based treatment and clinical research?

In fact, clinical research is also clinical work. However, in the course of clinical research work, there are strict restrictions on whether research drugs can be used or not, it also limited the control group or all groups to the same standard specification.

"I think that for any doctor to participate in a clinical study, there has to be a commitment and a commitment to follow the standard, which limits the ability of the clinician to prescribe and dispose in a way that is particularly individualized and often lacks evidence-based medical evidence. "

Cao Bin emphasized, "I am not opposed to the inclusion of evidence-based medicine in clinical practice, but if it is not proven, it must be subject to standards that do not allow the overuse of unproven treatments or drugs. "

Question 7: How to understand evidence-based treatment during a new crown epidemic?

Cao Bin says that before doing a randomized double-blind control of Klebsiella, they had actually observed that Klebsiella was effective in more than 20 cases, but that "if we continue to look at 20 cases, it may not be effective again. ". Therefore, prospective randomized controlled studies are necessary to answer questions about the efficacy of each therapy.

"Why were we able to target cleats and Ridgeville? Just because read a book, read the literature, if not read a book, Do not read the literature, then how can we know there are two drugs in the world? I think that's the first step."

The second requirement is suspicion. "Don't, don't, don't, don't, don't, don't, don't, don't, don't, don't, don't, don't, don't, don't, don't, don't, don't, don't, don't, don't, don't, don't, don't, don't, don't, don't, don't, don't, don't, don't, don't, don't, do

"One of the things we say over and over again about training medical students and doctors in training is that working long hours doesn't mean you have experience. In fact, our accumulation of experience must be built on the basis of evidence. Because we specialize in pneumonia, for example, a medical team treated 100 patients a month, and how many of those 100 patients could really tell the story? Is the etiology clear? Is the patient as well treated as expected based on the results of the Antimicrobial Susceptibility Test? And is the clinical presentation consistent with what we already know?"

Even if only one patient in 100 patients a month has evidence based medicine, that's a very valuable experience, Cao Bin says. One patient is experience, and you're not going to get any valuable experience managing 99 other patients, and you're going to take the wrong experience and you're going to hurt your next patient even more.
